%I A396633 #17 Jul 06 2026 16:43:54
%S A396633 2,3,5,7,13,17,37,79,149,157,167,179,347,359,389,1237,1249,1259,1279,
%T A396633 1789,3467,3469,12689,13457,13469,13789,15679,34589,345689,1235789
%N A396633 Primes with strictly increasing decimal digits whose digit reversal is also prime.
%C A396633 The sequence is finite since it is a subsequence of A052015, which has only 100 terms, and complete.
%D A396633 149 is a term since it is prime and 1 < 4 < 9 strictly increase and its reversal 941 is prime.
%D A396633 1237 is a term since it is prime with 1 < 2 < 3 < 7, and its reversal 7321 is prime.
%D A396633 139 is not a term: it is prime with strictly increasing digits but its reversal 931 is not prime.
%e A396633 (PARI) isok(p) = my(d=digits(p)); for(i=2, #d, if(d[i]<=d[i-1], return(0))); isprime(fromdigits(Vecrev(d)));
%e A396633 select(isok, primes([2, 1235789]))
%t A396633 Select[Prime[Range[PrimePi[1235789]]], Less @@ IntegerDigits[#] && PrimeQ[IntegerReverse[#]] &]
%Y A396633 Intersection of A007500 and A052015.
%Y A396633 Subsequence of A046732.
%Y A396633 Subsequence of A006567 apart from the single-digit terms.
%Y A396633 Cf. A024770 (right-truncatable primes), A068652 (circular primes).
%K A396633 nonn,base,fini,full,easy,new
%O A396633 1,1
%A A396633 _Mohd Anwar Jamal Faiz_, Jun 29 2026
